This paper deals with the capacity problem in wireless networks, which is a topic in the field of computer networks. The paper specifically models networks as random unit-disk graphs, which is a common approach in the study of wireless networks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). 

The paper also involves the analysis of multicommodity flows, which is a topic in the field of information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is also a likely sub-category. 

The paper uses a proof technique to obtain a tight characterization of the solution to the linear program associated with the multiflow problem. This involves the use of discrete probability tools, which suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) may also be a relevant sub-category. 

The paper also analyzes network capacity for different transmitter/receiver architectures, which involves the study of network topology and graph theory. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) may also be a relevant sub-category. 

Finally, the paper derives and strengthens the results of a previous study using only elementary counting and discrete probability tools. This suggests that cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) may also be a relevant sub-category.
